\i0\fs24 \cf0 Page 21:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 the clerk Richard \'91Citizen\'92 Lee, who first appeared in print as the religious poet \'91Ebenezer\'92, before the period of a few months transformed him into Citizen Lee, a journey traced more fully in Chapter 5\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 21:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Literary aspirations were not necessarily the equivalent of a desire for self-expression that placed a premium on the individual over the struggle\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 21:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Men like Reid and Thelwall may have been first drawn to a career in print on the assumption that the republic of letters in its proper form was a sphere open to talents underwritten by the freedom of the press, but they soon discovered that this was far from the case and pressed for a more genuinely accessible domain\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 21:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 In so far as they can be reconstructed from the archive, these backstories also indicate that the popular radicalism of the 1790s was the product of forces that reached back before 1789, even as they were crucially influenced by the sense of the French Revolution as an unprecedented event.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 21:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 radicalism in the 1790s was not the expression of a coherent ideological code or language, but the product of the social practices of the surrounding culture\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "highlights://Print__Publicity__and_Popular_Radicalism_in_the_1790s#page=23"}}{\fldrslt 
