\i0\fs24 \cf0 Page 25:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Part I of this book explores these conditions of mediation. Chapter 1 is concerned with the key concepts of print and publicity and their relation to complicating issues of space and gender.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "highlights://Print__Publicity__and_Popular_Radicalism_in_the_1790s#page=26"}}{\fldrslt 
\i\b\fs22 \cf3 Page 26}}
\i\b\fs22 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\i0\fs24 \cf0 Page 26:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 As with much of the broader associational world of clubs and societies, women seem to have played little official part in the popular radical societies\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 26:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 More generally, though, the LCS seems to have conformed to masculine definitions of citizenship and related practices, not least in the homosocial environment of singing and toasting at dinners.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 26:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Chapter 2 takes a chronological route through 1792\'965, tracing the way in which print formats and practices were elaborated and tested across different popular radical groups\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 26:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 How were they to identify and give form to the \'91general will\'92 of the people?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 26:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 The commitment to the circulation of political information in the societies accepted Rousseau\'92s assumption that \'91the general will is always right, but the judgment by which it is directed is not always sufficiently informed\'92.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "highlights://Print__Publicity__and_Popular_Radicalism_in_the_1790s#page=27"}}{\fldrslt 
\i\b\fs22 \cf3 Page 27}}
\i\b\fs22 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\i0\fs24 \cf0 Page 27:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 \'91the scattered million\'92 and \'91the people\'92\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 27:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 In terms of their everyday practice, the primary focus of this book, the radical societies encouraged an ongoing process of debate indebted to Paine\'92s idea that \'91discussion and the general will, arbitrates the question, and to this private opinion yields with a good grace, and order is preserved uninterrupted\'92.36 They self-consciously tasked themselves with what Seth Cotlar calls \'91the difficult process of constructing and sustaining an incessantly deliberative, politically efficacious and professedly inclusive mechanism for forming and discerning the general will\'92.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 i.e., they're trying to carry out consensus-based decision making\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 27:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Gilmartin\'92s acknowledgement of an alternative tendency \'91to treat internal conflict as the consequence of error or government interference, something to be corrected rather than negotiated\'92. \'91Print magic\'92, understood, as it\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "highlights://Print__Publicity__and_Popular_Radicalism_in_the_1790s#page=28"}}{\fldrslt 
\i\b\fs22 \cf3 Page 28}}
\i\b\fs22 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\i0\fs24 \cf0 Page 28:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 rarely was, in its purest form, often represented differences only as the \'91prelude to some final reconciliation or union, not a permanent condition to be addressed through ongoing procedures of public arbitration.\'92\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 But this just sounds like the Sharehouse principle that all problems have solutions\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 28:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Thompson understood the LCS primarily in terms of a class coming to consciousness. Since then literary scholars and historians have offered a diversity of accounts that have moved on from the Thompsonian model in their accounts of the radical societies.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 28:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 I examine public lectures, toasting, tavern debates, and song, but also more mundane and less colourful associational practices, such as day-to-day editorial discussion about what to publish under the LCS\'92s name.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 28:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 This book is very much indebted to those enquiries, but is more concerned with the attempts of the societies to create a role within a broader public sphere prior to the narrowing of opportunity after the Two Acts passed into law.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "highlights://Print__Publicity__and_Popular_Radicalism_in_the_1790s#page=29"}}{\fldrslt 
\i\b\fs22 \cf3 Page 29}}
\i\b\fs22 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\i0\fs24 \cf0 Page 29:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 the role of print personality as a form of mediation, that is, both attacks on personalities by the radical press\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 29:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 but also the development of personae by writers and booksellers\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 29:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Many radical authors and booksellers created identities that functioned as nodal points in the flow of political information and could compete for attention in a world where personality was becoming a key aspect of publicity in the theatre and the newspapers.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "highlights://Print__Publicity__and_Popular_Radicalism_in_the_1790s#page=30"}}{\fldrslt 
\i\b\fs22 \cf3 Page 30}}
\i\b\fs22 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\i0\fs24 \cf0 Page 30:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Eaton at \'91the Cock and Swine\'92 and Lee at his \'91Tree of Liberty\'92 participated in a print marketplace where personality mattered as an interface between print and its readers.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 30:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Part II of this book attends to the question of personality by looking at Thelwall as one among four different radical careers. Two of my case studies, Robert Merry and Charles Pigott, were radicals from above\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 30:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Citizen Lee and John Thelwall are more obviously representative of the LCS\'92s claim to represent \'91the people\'92\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 30:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 For many, this broader moral programme depended on a religious vision of the \'91human\'92, although no less invested in various forms of print mediation, whereas for others religion contradicted what they saw as an Enlightenment imperative towards rational debate.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "highlights://Print__Publicity__and_Popular_Radicalism_in_the_1790s#page=31"}}{\fldrslt 
\i\b\fs22 \cf3 Page 31}}
\i\b\fs22 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\i0\fs24 \cf0 Page 31:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 More broadly, the radical societies continued to have strong international contacts\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Page 31:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf4 Popular radical publicity aimed, in Redhead Yorke\'92s words, at a \'91complete revolution of sentiment\'92.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
